Classic cox: sensitivity analysis in patients aged 65 and above

J.S. González-Martínez

2021-09-03

Below are the results for a sensitivity analysis in patients aged 65 and above. Only univariate models were developed.
Libraries required 
library(readr)
library(tidyverse)

Upload data 
all_df <- read.csv("all_merged.csv")

all_df <- all_df[, -1] #remove number of row column produced when file was written 

#filter data to exclude those who were below age 65 at time of entry

all_df <- all_df %>% 
  filter(age_entry >= 65)
Establish patients’ characteristics for analysis 
#develop a function to obtain quick frequency tables percentages

freq_per_info <- function(var) {#function to generate a table with frequencies and percentages
  library(epiDisplay) #library required 
  tab1(var, 
       sort.group = "decreasing",
       cum.percentage = T,
       graph = F)}

Analysis
Establish death event rules

Patients died during the study period if they:

  1. Had a date of death AND

  2. The date of death was before the cohort’s span end (2019-05-01)

max(all_df$max_dateobsv)
## [1] "2019-05-01"
all_df <- all_df %>% 
  mutate(event_death = ifelse(!is.na(Date_Of_Death) &
                            (Date_Of_Death <= (max(max_dateobsv))), 1, #died in study period
                            0)) %>% 
  mutate(event_death = as.numeric(event_death))

table(all_df$event_death) #quick distribution of censored (0) and uncesored observations (1)
## 
##     0     1 
## 29900 36719
Univariate models

Functionalise graph plotting

#function to customise plot of Schoenfeld's test results

plot_schoenfeld <- function(resx, var_name) {
  my_plot0 <- ggcoxzph(resx, 
                       title = print(paste("Schoenfeld's test results for", var_name)),
                       xlab = "Time (days)", 
                       ylab = print(paste("Beta(t) for", var_name)))
    
  return(my_plot0)}

#function to customise plots of survival curves (only works for continuous variables)

plot_surv <- function(fitobj, var_name, namesobj) { 
 my_plot1 <- ggsurvplot(fitobj, #default
           palette = "nejm", #default
           censor.size = 2, #default
           title = print("Survival probablity in OxNHS dementia patients: Age 65+"),
           subtitle = print(paste("Adjusted for", var_name)),
           font.subtitle = c(14, "italic"),
           xlab = "Time (days)", #default
           legend.title = str_to_title(var_name),
           legend.labs = namesobj)
    
  return(my_plot1)}
